      "id": 359631,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>A clever recent method of peptide synthesis involves formation of an amide bond by reaction of an <i>α</i>-keto acid with an <i>N</i>-alkylhydroxylamine:</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcmtaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--012896e0c8886dbc8b5fd032328e662074ddfb7d/OChem_26_EC_017.jpg\" alt=\"An alpha-keto acid reacts with hydroxylamine in the presence of N, N-dimethylformamide to form an amide, with carbon dioxide and water as the products.\">\n<p>The reaction is thought to occur by nucleophilic addition of the <i>N</i>-alkylhydroxylamine to the keto acid as if forming an oxime (Section 19.8), followed by decarboxylation and elimination of water. Show the mechanism.</p>",
